<taxonomicName id="849577E96D35E022CBB7F49AAC47A110" LSID="2B182C9D-0440-54F8-8FE1-52D0688C8B08" authority="Santam &amp; Girbal, 1998." authorityName="Santam &amp; Girbal" authorityYear="1998" class="Kickxellomycetes" family="Legeriomycetaceae" genus="Orphella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Orphella catalaunica" order="Orphellales" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" phylum="Zygomycota" rank="species" species="catalaunica">Orphella catalaunica Santam &amp; Girbal, 1998.</taxonomicName>
<figureCitation id="278AF26399AB7A74A01D5805BC85F825" captionStart="Figures 21–25" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figures 21 - 25. Various species of Orphellales. 21 Orphella catalaunica from Leuctridae nymphs, trichospores and accompanying cells 22, 23 Orphella coronata from Nemouridae nymphs 22 allantoid trichospores and accompanying cells 23 zygospores produced homothallically 24, 25 Orphella helicospora from Leuctridae nymphs: 24 homothallical zygospores and accompanying cells 25 basal cell and holdfast. Scale bars: 25 μm in all figures." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.67.52055.figures21-25" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/414543" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">Fig. 21</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8A5AAF997A474A1AE68A727352915CD8" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph id="405B252659D1DD14121781B1004B1096" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">Specimens examined.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="71C10EFF577AA26883350535DDC50E00" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">Site 4: slides BUL-4-1, BUL-4-5, BUL-4-7; site 7: slide BUL-7-6.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="49D4353EEA26CF32898CA260BDFC9DC9" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" type="notes">
<paragraph id="C5CFF51F198953D86E0FFB5FA1341332" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="867610BC056E4995B934C7E46ED421DA" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">
We found this species associated with 
<taxonomicName id="BAE31902B90D77C3CE05BFC44F2AE1F0" class="Insecta" family="Leuctridae" genus="Leuctra" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Leuctra hippopus" order="Plecoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hippopus">
<emphasis id="9D56308D4A5923910B640163F8156F88" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">Leuctra hippopus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Kempny 1899) in two Bulgarian rivers and streams. The specimens examined had the typical characteristics of the species, including the straight trichospores measuring 47-56 
<normalizedToken id="0AB19339B20477F220B68E231085717A" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
5-7 
<normalizedToken id="A9B63C5977475CCA026C1886B77F6D98" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
in our collections, with generative cells 21-26 
<normalizedToken id="9A6A62E537734DAD76AF1132388160D1" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
long and a supporting cell 6-8 
<normalizedToken id="95FF4C460115EAD4EADE9F1B1B4C02E0" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
length (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="8A50EE0A8D7922CDE84D99C6386EFA20" captionStart="Figures 21–25" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figures 21 - 25. Various species of Orphellales. 21 Orphella catalaunica from Leuctridae nymphs, trichospores and accompanying cells 22, 23 Orphella coronata from Nemouridae nymphs 22 allantoid trichospores and accompanying cells 23 zygospores produced homothallically 24, 25 Orphella helicospora from Leuctridae nymphs: 24 homothallical zygospores and accompanying cells 25 basal cell and holdfast. Scale bars: 25 μm in all figures." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.67.52055.figures21-25" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/414543" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">21</figureCitation>
). All the characters of trichospores and accompanying cells fit the description of the species (
<bibRefCitation id="E9897A973D5F2DE868EC0AF4BDDA74E7" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1017/S0953756297004607" author="Santamaria, S" journalOrPublisher="Mycological Research" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" pagination="174 - 178" refId="B48" refString="Santamaria, S, Girbal, J, 1998. Two new species of Orphella from Spain. Mycological Research 102: 174 - 178, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1017/S0953756297004607" title="Two new species of Orphella from Spain." url="https://doi.org/10.1017/S0953756297004607" volume="102" year="1998">Santamaria and Girbal 1998</bibRefCitation>
). Zygospores were not seen on this occasion. This species was described from Catalonia, Spain (
<bibRefCitation id="46609CFF024AD2781A183182B1FCE4F3" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1017/S0953756297004607" author="Santamaria, S" journalOrPublisher="Mycological Research" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" pagination="174 - 178" refId="B48" refString="Santamaria, S, Girbal, J, 1998. Two new species of Orphella from Spain. Mycological Research 102: 174 - 178, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1017/S0953756297004607" title="Two new species of Orphella from Spain." url="https://doi.org/10.1017/S0953756297004607" volume="102" year="1998">Santamaria and Girbal 1998</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="50C7BE53030078AC0A580D118F55A845" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/15572536.2006.11832740" author="Valle, LG" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" pagination="1335 - 1347" refId="B66" refString="Valle, LG, Santamaria, S, 2005. Zygospores as evidence of sexual reproduction in the genus Orphella. Mycologia 97: 1335 - 1347, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/15572536.2006.11832740" title="Zygospores as evidence of sexual reproduction in the genus Orphella." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/15572536.2006.11832740" volume="97" year="2005">Valle and Santamaria 2005</bibRefCitation>
) and has been reported also from Norway (
<bibRefCitation id="23568F8E8F1CB968AF0D78015AC3396C" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/15572536.2005.11832936" author="White, MM" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" pagination="891 - 910" refId="B72" refString="White, MM, Lichtwardt, RW, 2004. Fungal symbionts (Harpellales) in Norwegian aquatic insect larvae. Mycologia 96: 891 - 910, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/15572536.2005.11832936" title="Fungal symbionts (Harpellales) in Norwegian aquatic insect larvae." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/15572536.2005.11832936" volume="96" year="2004">White and Lichtwardt 2004</bibRefCitation>
), France (
<bibRefCitation id="4152A82931F52890AB626E8B5F4F2253" DOI="https://doi.org/10.3852/13-129" author="Valle, LG" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" pagination="1607 - 1617" refId="B60" refString="Valle, LG, 2013b. Consolidating the legacy of JF Manier: new species and records of trichomycetes from France. Mycologia 105: 1607 - 1617, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3852/13-129" title="Consolidating the legacy of JF Manier: new species and records of trichomycetes from France." url="https://doi.org/10.3852/13-129" volume="105" year="2013 b">Valle 2013b</bibRefCitation>
) and Italy (
<bibRefCitation id="F394CB995B33D68F0BE90CBC9C6D171F" DOI="https://doi.org/10.3852/13-349" author="Valle, LG" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" pagination="589 - 606" refId="B68" refString="Valle, LG, Rossi, W, Santamaria, S, 2014. Orphella intropus (Kickxellomycotina), a new insect endosymbiont with an unusual perforating holdfast system and other trichomycetes from Italy. Mycologia 106: 589 - 606, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3852/13-349" title="Orphella intropus (Kickxellomycotina), a new insect endosymbiont with an unusual perforating holdfast system and other trichomycetes from Italy." url="https://doi.org/10.3852/13-349" volume="106" year="2014">Valle et al. 2014</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
